<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="77" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Haiti, Dominican Republic, Puerto Rico, and U.S. Virgin Islands.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="77" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Forests from sea level to 1000 m, primarily on calcareous soils, but in Puerto Rico also on serpentine-derived soils.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="77" type="phenology">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Flowering primarily January to April, rarely as early as November. Fruiting February to August.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="77" type="conservation status">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
Least concern. 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Drypetes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Geraniales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="alba">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Drypetes alba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
var. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">alba</emphasis>
is widespread and likely secure in the Dominican Republic, Puerto Rico, and U.S. Virgin Islands. It may be vulnerable or endangered in Haiti due to extensive deforestation there; I have seen no specimens from Haiti collected later than 1929.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
